AUDIENCE: So if we want to
become more of an optimist,

00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:35.460
what would you say
is the first step?

00:48:35.460 --> 00:48:36.544
Like, how would you start?

00:48:36.544 --> 00:48:38.501
DERRICK CARPENTER: Yeah,
it's a great question.

00:48:38.501 --> 00:48:40.240
There's a lot of
research specifically

00:48:40.240 --> 00:48:44.990
on how optimists think, and what
they do in adverse situations.

00:48:44.990 --> 00:48:46.990
But I think just
flat out, the key

00:48:46.990 --> 00:48:49.960
is that optimists identify
what they can control.

00:48:49.960 --> 00:48:53.740
So I think to practice
thinking more like an optimist,

00:48:53.740 --> 00:48:56.650
the next time you find yourself
in a situation that's maybe

00:48:56.650 --> 00:49:00.200
frustrating, or maybe
you're feeling impatient,

00:49:00.200 --> 00:49:03.250
maybe feeling anxious,
to train your mind

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:05.050
to immediately focus
on something you can

00:49:05.050 --> 00:49:06.620
do to improve the situation.

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:08.200
Even if it's, at
the very least, just

00:49:08.200 --> 00:49:10.300
internally, to
improve your emotions

00:49:10.300 --> 00:49:11.340
and how you're feeling--

00:49:11.340 --> 00:49:14.470
that what an optimist does is
finds those points of control

00:49:14.470 --> 00:49:16.520
and leverages the
heck out of those.

00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:19.600
So I think that alone
is going to get you

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:22.180
pretty far in terms of shifting
your thinking to a more

00:49:22.180 --> 00:49:24.710
optimistic style.

00:49:24.710 --> 00:49:25.440
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:49:25.440 --> 00:49:26.940
Another Dory
question, "How do you

00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:28.980
balance managing
negative thoughts

00:49:28.980 --> 00:49:31.230
without settling or
accepting situations

00:49:31.230 --> 00:49:32.400
that you should not be?

00:49:32.400 --> 00:49:35.220
For example, if in a
bullying work environment,

00:49:35.220 --> 00:49:37.180
or an unhappy
personal relationship,

00:49:37.180 --> 00:49:38.760
such as a marriage,
you definitely

00:49:38.760 --> 00:49:40.560
want to manage thoughts,
but you may want

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:41.991
to maintain your standards."

00:49:41.991 --> 00:49:42.990
DERRICK CARPENTER: Yeah.

00:49:42.990 --> 00:49:47.680
I think this just goes back to
the skill of assessing first.

00:49:47.680 --> 00:49:49.320
If you're having
negative thoughts

00:49:49.320 --> 00:49:53.190
that are honest and true
thoughts about a very hard

00:49:53.190 --> 00:49:55.730
situation you may be facing--

00:49:55.730 --> 00:49:57.990
the situations in life
aren't always easy.

00:49:57.990 --> 00:49:59.790
We all acknowledge
that as human beings.

00:49:59.790 --> 00:50:01.560
If you're in a
situation that's not

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:04.320
healthy for you, the negative
thoughts that are bubbling up

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:06.990
around that are, I think, a
clear message that's telling

00:50:06.990 --> 00:50:08.779
you, you have to do something.

00:50:08.779 --> 00:50:10.320
So those are not
the thoughts that we

00:50:10.320 --> 00:50:12.387
want to fight back
against or try to avoid.

00:50:12.387 --> 00:50:14.220
I think the more that
we can tune into those

00:50:14.220 --> 00:50:18.359
and allow them to guide
our responses, the better.

00:50:18.359 --> 00:50:18.900
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:50:18.900 --> 00:50:22.040
Last Dory question
is, "How can people

00:50:22.040 --> 00:50:24.500
relieve stress and
dread about things that

00:50:24.500 --> 00:50:26.750
are or feel truly unchangeable?

00:50:26.750 --> 00:50:29.990
For example, a project that you
know you cannot finish on time,

00:50:29.990 --> 00:50:32.600
an exam you know you are not
prepared for, a deadline that

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:35.030
you just realized you missed
that will adversely affect

00:50:35.030 --> 00:50:35.639
you."

00:50:35.639 --> 00:50:36.680
DERRICK CARPENTER: Great.

00:50:36.680 --> 00:50:37.180
Yeah.

00:50:37.180 --> 00:50:39.080
So I think this
goes back, again,

00:50:39.080 --> 00:50:42.500
to what an optimistic thinking
style is really about,

00:50:42.500 --> 00:50:44.510
acknowledging those
things we can't control,

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:46.070
and letting those things pass.

00:50:46.070 --> 00:50:47.820
Now, first off, I think
in those examples,

00:50:47.820 --> 00:50:50.600
something like a test you're
not feeling prepared for--

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:52.910
by all means, even if
the test is in an hour,

00:50:52.910 --> 00:50:54.770
an hour is a lot of
room to do something

00:50:54.770 --> 00:50:55.710
you have control over.

00:50:55.710 --> 00:50:56.630
So I would say an
optimist, first

00:50:56.630 --> 00:50:58.610
and foremost, wouldn't
let that thought go.

00:50:58.610 --> 00:51:00.484
They would do something
to prepare themselves

00:51:00.484 --> 00:51:01.920
as much as they
could in an hour.

00:51:01.920 --> 00:51:04.920
But if it's something you
really don't have control over,

00:51:04.920 --> 00:51:07.670
I think the skills
of distancing,

00:51:07.670 --> 00:51:09.380
to write about it
and journal about it,

00:51:09.380 --> 00:51:12.230
or to find a mindfulness or
meditation practice where

00:51:12.230 --> 00:51:15.082
you can just let these thoughts
come into your awareness

00:51:15.082 --> 00:51:16.790
and then acknowledge,
I can't do anything

00:51:16.790 --> 00:51:18.662
about this, whatever
emotions are coming up

00:51:18.662 --> 00:51:21.120
around this are there, but I'm
just going to let them pass.

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:22.536
And again, shift
my attention more

00:51:22.536 --> 00:51:24.980
towards what I can do
to improve my situation,

00:51:24.980 --> 00:51:27.059
to get myself into
a healthy place.

00:51:27.059 --> 00:51:28.100
Thank you guys very much.

00:51:28.100 --> 00:51:30.550
[APPLAUSE]

